WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.920
Hey everyone, my name is Cecil and I'm here with my colleague Jay and we're from the Posit

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:19.280
support team and today we're going to be walking you through how to connect to a database.

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:26.080
In this case we're using Microsoft SQL Server and we'll be doing this on the Linux Command

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:32.480
Line. It's a good idea to make sure that you can connect to your database from the Linux Command

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:38.639
Line before you try connecting through Posit Workbench or Posit Connect. So in this case

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:45.599
our SQL Server is just using local authentication which is just username and password. So if we

00:00:45.599 --> 00:00:53.599
open up the odbc.ini file, this is a file that we can use to test our database connection.

00:00:53.599 --> 00:01:01.360
So this will have our connection string specifying that we're using the Posit Pro drivers here so

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:10.080
the SQL Server driver, the IP of our SQL Server in this case, the database that we're using,

00:01:10.879 --> 00:01:18.080
the port, and the user id and password that we're connecting with. So now that we have that file

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:25.279
what we want to do is we can test connectivity outside of the product and through the Linux

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:34.959
Command Line with ISQL. So we can do isql-v sql-server-local which was the name of our dsn

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:41.199
and the dash v flag is just for verbosity in case the connection does fail we'll know why.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:49.839
So we can hit enter there and you'll see if it works we'll be thrown into a shell

00:01:49.839 --> 00:01:55.760
into our SQL Server. So from here we can validate that we're actually connected

00:01:55.760 --> 00:02:01.919
by just running a select command to show the schema. So there we can see the schema.

